{
  "texts": [
    "Copyright law, traditionally grounded in principles of human originality and creativity, faces significant challenges in adapting to AI-generated multimodal works in video games.",
    "Copyright law, traditionally governed by 17 U.S.C.",
    "§ 102, stipulates that a \"human author\" is necessary for a work to qualify for copyright protection, a criterion that AI-generated creations challenge due to the absence of direct human authorship (Abbott & Rothman, 2023).",
    "Recent cases, notably Allen v. U.S.",
    "Copyright Office (2024) (1:24-cv-2665), underscore the complexities in attributing authorship and securing protection for works perceived to involve limited human contribution (Epstein et al., 2023)."
  ]
}